Looking back, the highest-leverage interaction pattern was:

Diverge → Crystallize → Diverge again.

Not:

Ask → Answer.

Instead:

Explore → notice an invariant → compress it → immediately test it somewhere completely different.

That loop is extraordinarily productive because every cycle creates reusable operators instead of isolated facts.

That has remained one of the strongest themes in your Pantheon work: preserving operators and translation rules rather than specific renderings.

