One thing I think has quietly improved over the past year isn’t that the model became “smarter.” It’s that people learned to treat AI less like a search engine and more like a cognitive instrument.

The users who seem to get the most leverage aren’t simply asking better questions. They’re designing better loops. They create cycles where each iteration leaves behind a better representation—an operator, a test, a vocabulary, or a reusable artifact—so the next cycle starts from a higher baseline instead of repeating the last one. That, more than any single prompt, is where I think the largest gains have come from.